article.headline: Minnesota 79, UMKC 53
article.story:
KANSAS CITY, Mo. (AP) -- Minnesota advanced to the final 16 of
the NCAA tournament last March, and Missouri-Kansas City coach Dana
Eikenberg sees no reason why the Golden Gophers will not be back
there again.

"I think they can go far," Eikenberg said after a 79-53 loss
Sunday to ninth-ranked Minnesota. "I think they are really good."

Minnesota (7-0) was much too good for UMKC (2-4).

Lindsay Whalen scored 19 points, and Janel McCarville had her
fourth double-double of the season with 13 points and 15 rebounds.

"Lindsay is one my favorite players," Eikenberg said. "She
can do it all. I think McCarville is one of the best inside
players."

And the Golden Gophers have a strong bench led by freshmen Liz
Podominick, who had 14 points, and Kelly Roysland, who finished
with 10.

"We have a great point guard (Whalen) and a great center
(McCarville) and a great supporting cast," Minnesota coach Pam
Borton said. "I think we've got a lot of weapons on the floor."

Katie Houlehan led UMKC with 16 points, making all four of her
3s. Casey Ellis had 15 points, all in the first half, for the
Kangaroos, but left with an ankle injury with 14:34 to play and did
not return.

Minnesota, which led 38-29 at the break, scored the first seven
points to start the second half, when UMKC missed 10 of its first
13 shots. The Kangaroos made only 32.2 percent of their shots.

"We were a little sloppy in the first half, but I thought we
played better and more disciplined in the second half," Borton
said. "We did not make too many silly fouls in the second half."

Borton knew UMKC could make its season by upsetting her
undefeated Gophers.

"We have a bullseye on the back of our head in these
non-conference games," Borton said.

The Golden Gophers went on an 13-3 spree early in the game to
expand a one-point lead to 22-11 with 11:02 left in the first half.
Whalen scored four of her 10 first-half points in that stretch.

Ellis was the only offensive threat for the Kangaroos in the
opening 10 minutes, scoring UMKC's first 13 points. UMKC did not
get a basket from another player until Jayme Sweere scored with
8:07 left in the half.

Carlai Moore, UMKC's leading rebounder and second-leading
scorer, picked up two fouls in the first five minutes. She was
whistled for two more fouls in the first three minutes of the
second half. She fouled out with no points and three rebounds in
just 10 minutes of play.

Minnesota dominated inside, outscoring UMKC 48-10 in the paint
and pulling down 18 more rebounds.
